1.title: Italian Meatballs and Sausage
1.plot: John grew up in Queens and was raised in an Italian household. He cooks a recipe for Italian meatballs and sausage with tomato sauce that he learned from his Grandfather. John and his Mother tell us the story behind the dish.

2.title: Puerto Rican Shepherd's Pie
2.plot: Liz's Puerto Rican roots go deep in New York City; from Spanish Harlem, to the Lower East Side to Queens. Her Father taught her how to cook at a young age after her Mother passed away and through his recipes she connects with her Latin roots. She prepares a dish her Father created, a Puerto Rican version of a Shepherd's Pie.

3.title: Japanese Comfort Food
3.plot: Yuki shares her favorite traditional family comfort foods from Japan. She cooks these recipes when she's missing that 'ahhh' feeling of being home in Japan. Now living in Brooklyn, NY with her husband Dennis and daughter, these simple and shareable dishes have also become favorites of her family and friends.

4.title: Vegan Comfort Food
4.plot: After a rough childhood, John has taken on a positive approach to life that includes eating a plant based (vegan) diet. One dish he holds dear to his heart is meatloaf and mashed potatoes, a dish his Mother used to cook for him and his brothers. John shares his vegan version of his Mother's meatloaf, and the story of his life that you won't soon forget.

5.title: Italian Jamaican Fusion
5.plot: Dionne and her family immigrated to the Bronx from Jamaica in the 1970's. Moving in to the then mostly Italian neighborhood of Williamsbridge, Dionne's Mother learned how to cook Italian food from neighbors. As a child, Dionne learned her Mother's Italian cooking skills in the very same kitchen she cooks in today.

6.title: Indian Curry
6.plot: Jai Sen shares a traditional family recipe for Bengali Shrimp Curry, an Indian dish his Mother taught him. Jai Sen's Mom is from Upstate New York and his Father from India and after they met and fell in love, they moved to India. The rest of Jai Sen's story is a delicious history.

7.title: Southern Soul Food
7.plot: Alysa follows her family food roots from her current home in Harlem, all the way back to Albany, Georgia where she would visit her Grandmother on her farm as a child. She shares recipes for smothered pork chops, sweet potato casserole, and mac n' cheese with her family of friends in New York.

8.title: Mexican Traditions
8.plot: Born and raised in the Bronx, Renee learned how to cook from her Mexican tía abuela (great aunt). She was a strong, independent woman who had her own farm in Mexico, and taught Renee a thing or two about life, love, and best of all, food.

9.title: Chinese Traditions
9.plot: Jenny is 90 years old. Her ultimate joy in life is her family, especially cooking for them. She shows off her super fast, awe inspiring, and quick-witted cooking skills, creating traditional Chinese dishes her family has enjoyed their entire lives. Having these recipes is something her family will cherish for years to come, a truly special moment in all of their lives.

10.title: Italian Cutlets and Stuffed Artichokes
10.plot: Peter shares a beautiful New York story matched with delicious Italian recipes. His family has deep Italian roots all over the city. He shows us how to make his Aunt's chicken cutlets (his childhood favorite) and his family's 'special occasion' stuffed artichokes.

11.title: Haitian Soup Joumou
11.plot: Jame's favorite dish his Mother makes for him is traditional Haitian Soup Joumou, but she has never taught him how to make it...until now. She stops by his apartment to teach him how to make this heart warming dish and share a few of her own surprising food stories from growing up in Haiti.

1.title: Southern Sunday Dinner
1.plot: Sabrina shares a traditional Georgian family meal by cooking a full Southern Sunday Dinner complete with fried chicken, mashed potatoes, biscuits, blackberry cobbler, and sweet iced tea.

2.title: New England Seafood
2.plot: The Foley Family shares their spin on a traditional seafood bake, a recipe a close family friend taught them.

3.title: New Orleans BBQ
3.plot: Newly Weds Chris & Crystal have started their own family tradition which includes Chris' Cola Q Bar-B-Q sauce and Crystal's Grandmothers sweet potato pie.

4.title: Mexican
4.plot: Our guest Judith and her daughter Judy make a traditional Mexican Molcajete that was passed down from Judith's Mother.

5.title: Vietnamese
5.plot: Quan shares a recipe he learned from his Vietnamese Aunt. Goi Cuon, a spring roll filled with fried fish, boiled shrimp, and served with a peanut sauce.

6.title: Vegan Indian/French
6.plot: Cindy puts her own vegan twist on a recipe that draws influence from the West Indian side of her family and French food that she loves. Her tomato based vegan ratatouille is one her friends love.

7.title: Polish
7.plot: After emigrating from Poland to the US when Joanna was a young girl, her Father taught her how to make this traditional Polish beef stew with their own family twist. Her Father joins her in the kitchen as they prepare a pot for the family.

8.title: Jamaican
8.plot: Kimbelyn and her Mother make a traditional Jamaican dish, Oxtails. They serve it up with peas and rice and fried plantains.

9.title: Brazilian
9.plot: Lucia makes Peixada, a Brazilian fish stew that her Father used to make when she was a child.

10.title: Italian
10.plot: Bill's parents owned their own restaurant when he was growing up which sparked his interest in cooking. He hits the kitchen with his Mom to cook cheese filled crepe manicotti and beef braciole, two staple Italian dishes.

11.title: New England Comfort Food
11.plot: The Foley Family shares their spin on a traditional seafood bake, a recipe a close family friend taught them. Peter, the kitchen magician of the family, makes a simple yet 'knock-your-taste-buds-off' cocktail sauce to go along with their seafood mélange.

12.title: English
12.plot: Grant fires up his kitchen with his English Mother cooking a chicken divan recipe she made for him when they used to live in Wimbledon. Grant then shows off his own culinary skills preparing a steak au poivre with scalloped potatoes.

13.title: Thai Fusion
13.plot: Matt grew up in West Africa where seafood was abundant and then spent time in his college years traveling through Thailand. These two influences and his Chef-Step-Mother spawned this creation, lime chili calamari, amazing.

1.title: Southern Shrimp n' Grits
1.plot: George's Southern Shrimp n Grits are out of this world. His laughter and love fill the kitchen as he generously prepares this family dish, one his father passed on to him. Don't forget to add 'nature's candy. Bacon!'.

2.title: Roasted Chicken and Fried Green Tomatoes with Texas Sheet Cake
2.plot: Trish knows her way around the kitchen that's for sure. This no nonsense Texan likes to keep it simple and delicious and shows us how to make just a few of her family's favorites: roasted chicken, fried green tomatoes, and a 'wow!' factor chocolate sheet cake.

3.title: Triggerfish Chowder with Strawberry Shortcake
3.plot: The Gast Family treat us to some fresh Florida seafood with this Triggerfish chowder recipe, chock full of ocean fare. The Mom, Chris, steps in to show us a simply sweet recipe for fresh Florida strawberry shortcake, A perfect meal.

4.title: Red Velvet Cake
4.plot: Vonda's Red Velvet Cake is the sweetest, smoothest, and most moist we have ever had. In addition to the heaping doses of love she puts in to this cake, she has a few secret tips to share as well. You won't want to forget this recipe, ever.

9.title: Fried Apple Pie
9.plot: After the day her home-town matriarch declared on her birthday that her amazing dessert was 'just fried pies', Rose fell in love with perfecting these sweet little pockets of deliciousness. Filled with hot gooey apples, these fried pies are best served with a bourbon punch cocktail, and a little ginger ice cream.

11.title: Lebanese Stuffed Eggplant and Bread Pudding
11.plot: The Elkhouri Family has food running deep within their soul. The owner of Cedar's Cafe, family mom Marlene, makes sure she instills the gift of cooking in all of her children's lives. In this episode, her and her daughter Toni make some Lebanese favorites.

12.title: Traditional Indian Lamb Biryani and Baghare Baingan
12.plot: The entire Imami family gets involved when preparing this traditional Indian feast. Layers of amazing Indian spices give mouth watering depth to these surprisingly simple recipes steeped in their family's history.

14.title: Southern Pulled Pork and BBQ
14.plot: Friends Bart and Marc love BBQ. Their families come together to share their uniquely different styles of BBQ. Bart, from South Carolina, makes a slow smoked ham with a secret vinegar based sauce complimented with a traditional family coleslaw recipe. Marc makes sauce-less yet more traditional style smoked BBQ ribs that he loves to share.

Guests share the history and culture behind their dish and then prepare the meal for family and friends..
